ckaging that&rsquo;s suitable for food use. Suitable packaging is marked &lsquo;for food contact&rsquo; or has a symbol on it that looks like a wine glass and a fork.</p>\n\n<p>There are special rules for using plastics, ceramics or cellophane for packaging. You must have written evidence that you&rsquo;ve kept to them.</p>\n\n<p>This is known as a &lsquo;declaration of compliance&rsquo; and you can get it from your packaging supplier. You also have to get one if you buy food that&rsquo;s already packaged for sale in any of those materials.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.food.gov.uk/multimedia/pdfs/publication/legalcompliancefoodpackaging.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Guidance on materials in contact with food' (PDF, 446KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Guidance on materials in contact with food’ (PDF, 446KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Food assurance schemes</h2>\n\n<p>You could also join voluntary food assurance schemes such as <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.redtractor.org.uk/Home\" title=\"Find out more about Red Tractor\">Red Tractor</a> or <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.lioneggs.co.uk/page/lionmark\" title=\"Find out more about Lion Eggs\">Lion Eggs.</a> These schemes let customers known food has been produced to certain standards eg on food safety or animal welfare.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/food-labelling-and-packaging/food-labelling-what-you-must-show","slug":"food-labelling-what-you-must-show","order":2,"title":"Food labelling - what you must show","body":"<p>For food sold pre-packed, you must be able to see all this information when you look at the front of the product:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>the name of the food</li>\n  <li>a &lsquo;best before&rsquo; or &lsquo;use by&rsquo; date (or where to find it)</li>\n  <li>quantity</li>\n  <li>any necessary <a href=\"/food-labelling-and-packaging/food-and-drink-warnings\" title=\"Food warnings\">warnings</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You must also put these on the label, but they can be on the back or side of the product:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li><a href=\"/food-labelling-and-packaging/ingredients-list\" title=\"Ingredients list\">a list of ingredients</a> (if there are more than 2)</li>\n  <li>the name and address of the manufacturer, packer or seller</li>\n  <li>the lot number (or use-by date if you wish)</li>\n  <li>any special storage conditions</li>\n  <li>instructions for use or cooking, if necessary</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>What you might have to show</h2>\n<p>You must also show these if they apply to your product:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>a warning for drinks with an alcohol content above 1.2% </li>\n  <li>a warning if the product contains <abbr title=\"genetically modified\">GM</abbr> ingredients, unless their presence is accidental and 0.9% or less</li>\n  <li>a warning if the product has been radiated</li>\n  <li>the words &lsquo;packaged in a protective atmosphere&rsquo; if the food is packaged using a packaging gas</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Country of origin</h2>\n<p>The label for beef, veal, fish and shellfish, honey, olive oil, wine, most fruit and vegetables and poultry imported from outside the <abbr title=\"European Union\">EU</abbr> must show the country of origin.</p>\n\n<div class=\"form-download\">\n<p><a href=\"http://www.food.gov.uk/multimedia/pdfs/originlabellingguid0909.pdf\" title=\"Download 'Country of Origin labelling guidance' (PDF, 180KB)\" rel=\"external\">Download ‘Country of Origin labelling guidance’ (PDF, 180KB)</a></p>\n</div>\n\n<p>You must also show the country of origin if customers might be misled without this information, eg if the label for a pizza shows the leaning tower of Pisa but the pizza is made in the UK.</p>\n\n<h2>Special rules for some products</h2>\n<p>If you supply any of the following, there are special rules about <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.defra.gov.uk/food-farm/food/standards/\" title=\"Specific food labelling requirements\">what you can call them and what you have to show on the label.</a></p>\n